comment.body:
```ts
import { createApp } from './entry.js' with { viteEnvironment: 'ssr' }
import { renderToString } from 'vue/server-renderer'

export default (request) => {
  const app = createApp()
  const html = await renderToString(app)

  return new Response(html)
}
```

The `./entry.js` needs to be defined in the SSR environment's `entries` too so we don't need to look for it dynamically. 

When bundled, the import turns into a normal import from an `ssr` environment bundle

During dev, we create a separate module runner that shares `evaluatedModules`, but fetches modules from specified (`ssr` in this case) environment. I do have a concern though - if two environments import the same module they might/will be bundled differently, but module runner cannot distinguish them because it uses only the module id. So we might actually have to use separate module graphs for different runners too.

